   PRIVACY POLICY

     This page best viewed at 600 x 800 pixels using Microsoft Internet
           Explorer 4 or higher or Netscape Navigator 4 or higher.

   [jump directly to chart listing]

   The history of Montana is as colorful and diverse as the state's rugged
   geography.  No less intriguing are the individuals who have represented
   the Treasure state in the U.S. Congress.

   These forty-eight individuals have, in large part, shaped the Montana
   we know today.  Their lives reflect the potential and the aspirations
   of the Montanans they represent(ed) in Congress.

   The history of Montana is relatively short.  But it should not be
   forgotten.  The attitudes of Montanans are deeply rooted in the state's
   past.  To meet the challenges and opportunities of Montana's future, we
   must attempt to understand her past.  It is for this reason that this
   project was conceived.  The portraits and biographies are the product
   of numerous voluntary efforts, principally by the members of my staff
   who meet periodically to discuss and research Montana history.

   I hope that you enjoy this display.  May it provide a new insight to
   rekindle an interest in Montana history. Please note that all
   photographs displayed in conjunction with this project were provided by
   either the Library of Congress or the Montana Historical Society.

                  Max Baucus

   The following pictures and biographies are permanently displayed in the
   Mike Mansfield Room in Senator Baucus' Washington, D.C. office

